{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"904d3187-29cf-4dbb-9829-32a150855e7c","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduced **first-class span types** with implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution:\n\n| .NET 9 (C# 13) | .NET 10 (C# 14) |\n|---|---|\n| `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` ✅ preferred |\n\n`MemoryExtensions.Contains` wins because `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is more specific than `IEnumerable<int>`. But expression trees **cannot represent ref structs** like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the tree construction/interpretation blows up at runtime.\n\n## How to fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains` again. Any of these work:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: Explicit static call (clearest)\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n\n// Option 2: Cast away the span conversion\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 3: AsEnumerable() (same idea, more fluent)\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);\n```\n\nAll three force resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which operates on `IEnumerable<T>` and is fully compatible with expression trees.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"be16107e-925a-48df-8f66-92818dbdca61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves extension methods. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension members** (a new feature), but more relevantly, there's a change in overload resolution for `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` vs the array-specific methods.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Array` or arrays got new instance methods or there were changes to how `Contains` is resolved.\n\n\nI'm reconsidering the core issue here—it probably involves how `Contains` resolution changed between versions, where .NET 9 would resolve `array.Contains(num)` as an extension method call to `Enumerable.Contains`, but .NET 10 might have introduced a different resolution path that affects how expression trees capture this call. arrays implement `IReadOnlyList<T>` or some other interface change, or there's a new `Contains` method somewhere that changes resolution.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is related to **the new `CountBy` / extension member changes**, or more likely, the change where `System.Linq.Enumerable` methods got updated.\n\nWait, let me reconsider. I think the actual breaking change in .NET 10 is:\n\n**`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** - In .NET 10, `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are more heavily used. Arrays implicitly convert to spans. There might be a resolution change where `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (which works on `Span<T>`) instead of `Enumerable.Contains` (which works on `IEnumerable<T>`).\n\n`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` operates on spans, which are ref structs and can't be used in expression trees. So in .NET 10, when arrays implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, the overload resolution now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains`, but expression trees reject ref struct parameters entirely.\n\nThe user says it \"throws at runtime,\" which suggests the expression tree might compile but fail when executed. This could happen if the expression tree is constructed dynamically or if there's a runtime check that catches the span-based call.\n\nActually, I think I've got it now—in .NET 10 with C# 14, the implicit span conversions changed. Arrays can now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, which means the compiler might be resolving `Contains` to a span-based overload that expression trees can't handle, causing a runtime failure when the expression is compiled or interpreted. The user's code is creating an expression tree with `Contains` on an array, then compiling it—so the compiler should resolve `Contains` to `Enumerable.Contains` since expression trees can't use span-based methods. But if C# 14 changed how overload resolution works, maybe the compiler is now picking `MemoryExtensions.Contains` and the expression tree fails at runtime when it tries to interpret a ref struct operation, or perhaps the compiler still picks `Enumerable.Contains` but something else about the runtime behavior changed in C# 14. C# 14's implicit span conversions are likely causing `array.Contains(x)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, which creates a problem when the expression tree interpreter tries to handle a method reference to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` at runtime.\n\nThe compiler might not catch this at compile time due to how the new span conversions interact with expression tree validation, so the code compiles successfully but fails when executed. The fix would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` to force the original resolution path. I'm uncertain whether this is a compile-time or runtime error in C# 14, but the user reports it happens at runtime, which suggests either the compiler has a gap or something more subtle is happening with overload resolution in expression tree contexts. Let me consider that the compiler might correctly route to `Enumerable.Contains` for expression trees (since spans aren't allowed), but there could be a runtime change in .NET 10 affecting how that method behaves or how expression trees interpret it. I'll go with the most likely explanation: the implicit span conversion in C# 14 is the breaking change when `array.Contains(num)` runs in code targeting .NET 10 and C# 14. Outside expression trees: resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` — works fine, potentially faster\n- Inside expression trees: This resolution is problematic because expression trees can't handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>`\n\nThe exact failure mode (compile-time vs runtime) depends on implementation details. The user says runtime, so I'll trust that.\n\nActually, I just realized something. Let me reconsider. Perhaps the code compiles because:\n\n1. The C# 14 compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`\n2. For expression trees, it might try to emit a `MethodCallExpression` referencing that method\n3. Building the `Expression<Func<...>>` might succeed at compile time (the expression tree is built at runtime when the assembly loads, actually)\n4. But when the expression tree is constructed at runtime, it fails because you can't represent a `ReadOnlySpan<int>` parameter in an expression tree\n\nSo the error happens at runtime during expression tree construction or compilation/interpretation. The solution is to explicitly use `Enumerable.Contains` instead, which works with expression trees since it takes an `IEnumerable<T>` parameter. The runtime failure happens because the expression tree gets constructed from compiler-generated factory calls. I can offer three straightforward workarounds: explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains`, casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to sidestep the span conversion, or using `AsEnumerable()` to achieve the same effect.","outputTokens":3673,"requestId":"D81B:19EABB:617C47F:6A3F345:69F155ED"},"id":"e2bf72ab-6f56-47bb-9d78-fde67d754577","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:52:03.538Z","parentId":"e2927c2f-a8c3-498f-9381-e8f4aea62f08"}
